  <h2>This Is Bigger Than Parts</h2>
  <p>
    I started 3D3D to build functional parts. Marine fittings, automotive replacements, custom fabrication. That's the business. But the technology behind it, additive manufacturing, open-source design, distributed production, has implications that go way beyond replacing a broken radio knob.
  </p>

  <h2>Disaster Response</h2>
  <p>
    When infrastructure fails, hurricanes, earthquakes, floods, supply chains break down. Hardware stores are empty. Replacement parts don't exist locally. Shipping takes weeks if it works at all.
  </p>
  <p>
    A 3D printer with the right materials can produce pipe fittings, valve handles, bracket replacements, tool handles, and structural connectors on site. Not as a permanent solution, as a bridge. The thing that keeps the water system running until the real part arrives. Organizations like Field Ready have been doing this for years. It works.
  </p>

  <h2>Remote and Underserved Communities</h2>
  <p>
    There are communities. Indigenous communities in northern Canada, island nations in the Pacific, rural areas across Africa and South America, where getting a specific replacement part shipped in can take months and cost more than the item it's replacing. A small FDM printer with basic filament can produce functional household items, agricultural tool components, educational materials, and medical device accessories.
  </p>
  <p>
    The designs are already out there. Printables, Thingiverse, GrabCAD, tens of thousands of functional, tested designs available for free. The barrier isn't design. It's access to the machines and the knowledge to run them.
  </p>

  <h2>Open-Source Medical</h2>
  <p>
    This one matters. Open-source prosthetic hands, like the designs from e-NABLE, have been fitted on thousands of children. They're not titanium surgical implants. They're functional, affordable, replaceable assistive devices that cost a few dollars in filament instead of thousands in medical manufacturing.
  </p>
  <p>
    Stethoscopes, otoscopes, pill splitters, IV clamps, surgical tool handles, the open-source medical community has validated designs for all of these. Hospitals in developing countries are printing them today.
  </p>

  <h2>Why I Share the Files</h2>
  <p>
    Every design I publish on <a href="https://www.printables.com/@KTK3D_3050116" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Printables</a> is free. Not because I don't value the work, because the value multiplies when someone else can use it. A winch cup holder I designed for a sailboat might solve a completely different problem for someone I'll never meet. That's the point.
  </p>
  <p>
    3D3D is a business. I charge for fabrication, for expertise, for the time it takes to design and produce quality parts. But the files themselves? Those should be open. Always.
  </p>

  <h2>What You Can Do</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>If you have a working printer, look into local donation programs. Schools, libraries, and community centers often need functional prints, not toys, functional items.</li>
    <li>If you design parts, publish them. Printables, GitHub, wherever. License them openly.</li>
    <li>If you want to support work like this, <a href="https://ko-fi.com/3d3dca" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ko-fi</a> is the direct line. Part of what 3D3D does is contribute designs back to the community.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The technology exists. The designs exist. What's missing is enough people who know how to use it and are willing to share what they build. That's the gap worth closing.
  </p>
